Nonlinear regression

Computing

Neural networks

  1. Remove highly correlated predictors
  2. Preprocessing: center and scale

Yes, averaged models or neural nets in general are very susceptible to highly correlated variables. Therefore, it is necessary to remove highly correlated variables.

data(solubility)

rr length(too_high)

[1] 87

Alright, all the data is ready to feed into the model.

Now let’s create some grid search parameters for the neural net.

# This is essentially a cartesian product
nnet_grid <- expand.grid(.decay = c(0, 0.01, 0.1),
                         .size = c(1:10),
                         .bag = FALSE)


indx <- createFolds(train_sol, returnTrain = TRUE)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", index = indx)

rr workers=makeCluster(16,type=) registerDoParallel(workers)

rr nnet_tune <- train(train, train_sol, method = , tuneGrid = nnet_grid, trControl = ctrl, preProc = c(, ), linout = T, trace = T, MaxNWts = 10 * (ncol(train) + 1) + 10 + 1, maxit = 100)

Exercises

7.1 Support vector machine

  1. Fit different

rr rbfSVM <- ksvm(x = x, y = y, data = sinData, kernel =, kpar = , C = 1000000, epsilon = 0.1)

modelPrediction <- predict(rbfSVM, newdata = data_grid)

This is a matrix with one column. We can plot the

model predictions by adding points to the previous plot

plot(x, y) points(x = data_grid$x, y = modelPrediction[,1], type = , col = )

There is a tiny possibility that maybe I overfit my model a little bit. Just a tiny bit. Nothing too serious.

rr rbfSVM <- ksvm(x = x, y = y, data = sinData, kernel =, kpar = , C = 0.0000000001, epsilon = 0.1)

modelPrediction <- predict(rbfSVM, newdata = data_grid)

This is a matrix with one column. We can plot the

model predictions by adding points to the previous plot

plot(x, y) points(x = data_grid$x, y = modelPrediction[,1], type = , col = )

SVM with the lowest cost parameter is essentially a linear model.

rr rbfSVM <- ksvm(x = x, y = y, data = sinData, kernel =, kpar = list(sigma = 6), C = 0.25, epsilon = 0.1)

modelPrediction <- predict(rbfSVM, newdata = data_grid)

This is a matrix with one column. We can plot the

model predictions by adding points to the previous plot

plot(x, y) points(x = data_grid$x, y = modelPrediction[,1], type = , col = )

This one looks quite good. I’m essentially doing manual grid search for the best parameters. The author wants me to get an intuitive understanding of what these do. Epsilon flattens the line.

This works fine. I can’t really tell the difference between different parameters. Both sigma and the cost go from 0 = underfitting / linear model to overfitting. They are able to capture nonlinear relationships.
